The first time I had the croissant and a savory sandwich. Both were very delicious. The second time I had the hazelnut chocolate tart, which was very good. This time, I was kind of disappointed. The frangipane tart was good, but it didn't blow my mind like I thought Tartine would. The other three items were disappointing as well. I guess I really must have the banana cream tart next time, since that's what everyone says is a must-have at Tartine. Frangipane Tart: the description sounded so delicious I just had to have it. It's a tart filled with almond cream and topped with seasonal fresh fruits. This one looked like blackberry. The tart flaked easily with the touch of a fork. And the buttery flakes melted so easily in my mouth. The almond cream was interesting. There were big chunks of almonds and not so much of the "cream". The fruit was tart and delicious. It was a delicious tart! Almond Date Bread: I thought putting date in a quick bread is interesting. But I actually didn't like it much. Maybe the dates they used weren't the good kind, but it was just sweet, there wasn't any date flavor. But otherwise, it's very well made quick bread. Mexican Wedding Cookie: I've been having one of these at every bakery I see them in. Tartine's is very sweet and no chunky pecans. I like Pamplemousse's much better. Friand: very chocolatey. Not much more I can say.

    This was a last minute decision to stop by this bakery. It was late afternoon/early evening and I thought it would be quiet. I assumed this place would only be crazy in the mornings. I was shocked to see that there was still a line (out the door and curved around on the curb) this late on a Sunday evening. The line moved pretty fast so it wasn't so bad.

    From reviews, it seems the bread pudding and croissants are the best things to get here. We decided to get a chocolate croissant, a slice of tres leche cake, and to try on a whim the fangipane tart.

    - The Chocolate croissant is a MUST try! It was flaky and buttery, and the chocolate sat perfectly in the center and did not make the surrounding layers of the croissant mushy.
    - Tres leche cake was light, fluffy, and so good. I would highly recommend this too.
    - The fangipane tart was good but I wouldn't get it again. From the description it sounded like it would be fairly light. "Light almond-cream filling baked in a flaky pastry shell with seasonal fruit." I did not taste and almond cream filling. In fact, I don't remember even seeing a cream filling. It was a dense pastry that was heavily topped with blueberries (at least that was the only seasonal fruit I could taste).

    I definitely would say this place is worth a try :)

    7x7 100 Best Things To Eat In SF Before You Die 2013

    #24 Banana Cream Tart at Tartine Bakery

    As part of our March birthday celebration at work, our leadership team also got an entire order of the Banana Cream Tart along side the Princess Cake from Schuberts. My work is really big on the 7x7, yet another reason why I love working there!

    The tart is a challenge to serve due to its sheer size and unwillingness to be cut. That aside, the flavors were straight forward. The bananas and whipped cream were fresh and vibrant. I enjoyed the custard filling and thought it had great body to and not too sweet. As for the crust, it was thick and buttery but didn't wow me.

    Presentation was A+

    Overall Thoughts

    Worth a try on a smaller scale, perhaps an individual slice is best

    7x7 100 Best Things to Eat Before You Die 2012

    #24 Loaf of Bread Straight Out of Oven at Tartine Bakery

    An amazing rustic exterior delivering a sensational crunch in each bite. In contrast, the interior is pillowey soft yet provides a great chewy mouthfeel.

    The bread is quite good, the 2 previous failed attempts made this last venture that much sweeter with the taste of success!

    Overall Thoughts

    Great bread, great size, price is on the higher side ($8.25 a loaf) but well worth a try if you ever get the chance.

    P.S. don't worry if you think people will judge you for eating it as soon its out of the oven outside the front door, they will judge you if you dont!

    7x7 100 Things to Eat Before You Die 2012

    #7 Morning Bun from Tartine Bakery

    Randomly, my brother and sister brought over Tartine for breakfast one morning. I was amazed by their thoughtfulness for doing that but then to wait in line for Tartine so I can cross something off my list, that's just awesome!

    They ordered an array of pastries for us to try but in the end I wasn't completely floored as I would have liked. Don't get me wrong, it was good but wasn't "amazing". Everything was flaky and buttery with just a hint of sweetness as to not overwhelm your taste buds.

    We also tried the bread pudding, it was too eggy for my liking.

    Overall Thoughts

    I'm glad I got to try the morning bun but not sure if I would wait 1+ hour to get it again
